    </node>
    <node id="claim:0068">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Sorted records from DocSorter are pushed into a ZZZ folder that admins must manually clean up</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d20">When records are pushed from DocSorter they land in a folder with the prefix 'ZZZ' followed by the sorting session date. An administrator must then manually move the contents out of that folder and clean it up.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">2719.2</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "when we sort when when we push records from from doc sorter this is where it gets pushed to it actually gets pushed to it it has a funny folder name all of these folders will be in a single folder called zzz sorting session with the date and then someone that one of the administrators will then go and they will remove all of these folders out of that folder clean it up etc and that's what it looks like", "ts": 2719.2, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:14"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0069">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Sorted index hierarchy: trust/institution &gt; admission/event &gt; records</data>
      <data key="d2">0.95</data>
      <data key="d20">The sorted index is structured in three levels: first, the trust or medical institution; second, admissions or events (e.g. a hospital admission); third, the individual records belonging to that admission or event.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">2847.3</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "the first level would be the trust or the medical institution where the documents are from the and then second level would be any events or uh usually events but specifically admissions if a person who was in in admitted to a hospital that would usually be grouped as well so documents for that mission will be grouped underneath and then you've got the records that apply to that that event or admission", "ts": 2847.3, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "Index to Medical Records (Proposed 02.03.2024 - Total of 938 pages). A - University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust - Orla Grace Clayton. Pregnancy With Elijah 04.01.2020 - 26.11.2020: 01 Consultant Maternity Records; 02 Antenatal Records;", "ts": 2742.0, "source": "vision"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:15"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0070">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Grace Clayton is the recommended dev matter for exploring a complete sorted document set</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d20">The Grace Clayton matter on the dev environment is a useful reference case because it includes documents that went through a full sorting session, along with radiology, and has a realistic set of reports (early case assessment, chronology, schedule of radiology, clinical summary, file note).</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">2784.8</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "grace clayton is a good matter to look at okay because um the the documents that's here is what went through a sorting session and it's the the patient details is all a grace it's it's a dummy name obviously it's not it's not a real patient but all of these have been adapted for that", "ts": 2784.8, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "it also has um i think it's in my folder there is it in my folder yeah so there's an early case assessment there's a chronology there's a schedule of radiology so there are a few reports if you wanted to have a look at that clinical summary supportive there's a file note", "ts": 2812.7, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:15"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0071">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Index is structured per trust per patient, so the same trust appears twice for multi-patient cases</data>
      <data key="d2">0.95</data>
      <data key="d20">The index is organised per trust per patient, so in cases with multiple patients (e.g. mother and child) the same trust will appear as a duplicate entry, once for each patient.</data>
      <data key="d21">person:chantel-van-wyk</data>
      <data key="d22">[]</data>
      <data key="d23">fact</data>
      <data key="d24">False</data>
      <data key="d25">2888.1</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "it's a trust per um per patient by the way that's why you see two so you've got gp records same trust for all of grace clayton and then you've got the same trust for different patient which is the child elia elijah clayton and that's why you always always see duplicates provided both patients were at the same hospitals", "ts": 2888.1, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:15"]</data>
    </node>
